Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code contains **three** Thread.Abort patterns:

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Stop()` → `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | ThreadAbortException as control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | ResetAbort to continue execution | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it no longer injects a `ThreadAbortException`. Your `Stop()` method will crash, and the catch block is dead code.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();  // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for the thread to finish gracefully (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If the thread is still alive after 2s, it's a background thread —
        // it will be torn down at process exit. There is no safe force-kill
        // equivalent in modern .NET.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Critical Changes to `GetNextItem`

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or I/O), you **must** pass the token through — otherwise cancellation stalls until the blocking call returns on its own:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely, relied on Abort to interrupt
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever
}

// After (.NET 8) — wakes up when cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What happens |
|---|---|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | `Cancel()` fires but the thread stays blocked — `Stop()` hangs or returns with the thread still alive |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` without the `when` guard** | Swallows unrelated cancellations from inner calls — use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` |
| **Expecting `Cancel()` to be instant** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` runs for minutes between checks, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside it |
| **Using `Thread.Interrupt` as a fallback** | Also obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9). Use `CancellationToken` exclusively |

The fundamental shift: .NET Framework let the runtime **forcibly inject** an exception into any thread. .NET 8 requires the running code to **voluntarily check** for cancellation. Every blocking or long-running method in the call chain must accept and honor the `CancellationToken`.
